'''Kunitama''' (国魂) is a type of [[kami]] or god who acts as a [[tutelary deity]] or guardian of a [[province of Japan]] or sometimes other areas in Shinto.<ref name="nishioka-2">{{cite web |last=Nishioka |first=Kazuhiko |title=Kunitama |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=8983 |website=[[Kokugakuin University]] Encyclopedia of Shinto}}</ref><ref name="hardacre-2017a" />{{rp|102}}
The term is sometimes treated as a specific deity itself especially with [[Hokkaidō Shrine]],<ref name="hardacre-2017a" />{{rp|394}} and other colonial shrines,<ref name="koji-2010a" />{{rp|53–54}}<ref name="koji-2010a" />{{rp|217}} a or as an epithet in the case of [[Okunitama Shrine]]<ref name="nelson-1994a" /> or a part of a deity's name in the case of [[Yamato Okunitama]], whose name is also sometimes interpreted as an epithet.<ref name="ellwood-1990a" /><ref name="hardacre-2017a" />{{rp|22}}
== History == In ancient times it was believed that every province had a kunitama.<ref name="nishioka-2" />
[[Yamato Okunitama]] is the Kunitama of [[Yamato Province]]. He is sometimes identified with [[Ōmononushi]].<ref name="ellwood-1990a">{{Cite journal |last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |date=1990 |title=The Sujin Religious Revolution |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/30234018 |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=17 |issue=2/3 |pages=199–217 |doi=10.18874/jjrs.17.2-3.1990.199-217 |jstor=30234018 |issn=0304-1042|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name="hardacre-2017a">{{Cite book |last=Hardacre |first=Helen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Q81DQAAQBAJ |title=Shinto: A History |date=2017 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-062171-1 |language=en}}</ref>{{rp|22}}
As the [[Yamato court]] grew in power shrines were made in more and more places outside of the Yamato region.<ref name="hardacre-2017a" />{{rp|22}}
{{ill|Kunitama Okami|lt=Musahi no Okunitama|simple|Kunitama Omikami|ja|国魂}} of the [[Musashi Province]] was traditionally identified as [[Ōkuninushi]].<ref name="nelson-1994a" />
[[Hirata Atsutane]] said in his morning prayers that the deities to worship in [[Yamato Province]] were [[Ōmononushi]], [[Yamato Okunitama|Okunitama]], and [[Kotoshironushi]].<ref name="hardacre-2017a" />{{rp|343}}
[[Motoori Norinaga]] discussed the concept.<ref name="nishioka-2" /> {{Blockquote|text=Those virtuous kami who care for the land are called kunitama or kunimitama.<ref name="nishioka-2" />|author=[[Motoori Norinaga]]}}
