'''Kunitama''' (国魂) is a type of [[kami]] or god who acts as a [[tutelary deity]] or guardian of a [[province of Japan]] or sometimes other areas in Shinto.<ref name="nishioka-2">{{cite web |last=Nishioka |first=Kazuhiko |title=Kunitama |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=8983 |website=[[Kokugakuin University]] Encyclopedia of Shinto}}</ref><ref name="hardacre-2017a" />{{rp|102}}
The term is sometimes treated as a specific deity itself especially with [[Hokkaidō Jingu|Hokkaidō Shrine]],<ref name="hardacre-2017a" />{{rp|394}} and other colonial shrines,<ref name="koji-2010a" />{{rp|53–54}}<ref name="koji-2010a" />{{rp|217}} a or as an epithet in the case of [[Ōkunitama Shrine|Okunitama Shrine]]<ref name="nelson-1994a" /> or a part of a deity's name in the case of [[Yamato Okunitama]], whose name is also sometimes interpreted as an epithet.<ref name="ellwood-1990a" /><ref name="hardacre-2017a" />{{rp|22}}
